frameDefinitions: This frame is  concerned with the percepts that vibrations which travel through the air or another medium produce in hearing organs.
A Cognizer would engage in an Activity if asked or otherwise prompted to do so.
This frame contains nouns that refer to sensations in different modalities.
Ambient conditions of temperature, precipitation, windiness, and sunniness pertain at a certain Place and Time.
A physical entity, construed as a point-Sound_source, emits a Sound.
In this frame a Fluid moves from a Source to a Goal along a Path or within an Area.  '
frameExamples: I awoke to the <t>clash</t> of a jackhammer on concrete.
The court is <t>willing</t> to depart from the usual range of sentencing .
The huge sand dunes, perpetually changing, make for a surreal <t>sight</t>.
listRoleDefinitions: An entity that is construed as a single point source emitting sound.

The location at which sound is produced. This role differs from Location_of_sound_source in that it does not highlight the sound's spreading from its source to the perceiver's location, which is usually indicated by the preposition 'from'.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the individual that is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The <fen>Activity</fen> is what the <fen>Cognizer</fen> would do under certain circumstances.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role is only expressed with certain nouns in this frame, and then only with the help of a support verb, such as <ment>have</ment>:

This is the entity or phenomenon which gives rise to the sensation. In cases of veridical sensation, this role is not typically distinguished from <fen>Percept</fen>. Most of the phrases that express this role can be paraphrased as <ment>from</ment>-phrases, e.g.

The role <fen>Percept</fen> is used for phrases that express the characteristic property of a sensation. Typically this characteristic property is described with reference to the entity or phenomenon that produces the sensation---that  is why this role can be difficult to distinguish from Source. It is possible for Source and Percept to be expressed separately, however:

This role is assigned to phrases expressing the body part in which a sensation is located. Since touch is the least localized of sense modalities, words relating to haptic sensations are the ones most likely to occur with this FE:
This role is the perceptual background against which the Phenomenon is experienced by the Perceiver.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the sensation is perceived.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the weather occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the weather occurs.

The frame element <fen>Sound_source</fen> is assigned to a constituent referring to a physical entity which emits a sound. Such an entity must have an appropriately complex internal structure such that it can create a sound. For example, a machine or some other thing with moving parts can create sound by itself.

The frame element <fen>Sound</fen> is incorporated in the meaning of the verbs of this frame. Otherwise, this role is assigned to NPs which actually refer to a sound in the presence of the target. This typically occurs when the target is a verb used as a modifier in its <ment>-ing</ment> form, e.g.:
An event in which one or more <fen>Sound_source</fen>s participate and which is accompanied by <fen>Sound</fen>.
The time when the <fen>Noisy_event</fen> occurs.

The location of the <fen>Sound_source</fen>. This role differs from <fen>Location_of_source</fen> only in terms of point of view; the latter role implies a point of view that is not on the <fen>Sound_source</fen>.
<fen>Area</fen> is the setting in which the <fen>Fluid</fen>'s movement takes place on an unspecified <fen>Path</fen>.
<fen>Goal</fen> is the location the <fen>Fluid</fen> ends up.
The <fen>Path</fen> is the trajectory along which the <fen>Fluid</fen> moves.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the location the <fen>Fluid</fen> occupies initially.
The <fen>Fluid</fen> is the entity that changes location and moves in a fluidic way.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Fluid</fen> flows.
The Place describes the location of the motion which has a specified Source, Path or Goal.
listRoleExamples: He woke up because of the blare <fex>of a car horn</fex>.
There was a clatter of running feet <fex>in the street outside</fex>.
<fex>My mom</fex> is very loath to take any drugs without medical supervision.
Does biology really matter more than a willingness <fex>to take an active role in a child's life</fex>?
<fex>I</fex> have a tingling sensation in my hands.
The smell <fex>of the garlic</fex> made me hungry.
This herb gives off a smell <fex>of garlic</fex>.
I have a tingling feeling <fex>in my hands</fex>.
It's going to beep again <fex>in two minutes</fex>.
<fex>At Oregon Caves</fex>, a stream runs through the dining room.
